WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:20.000
We're continuing our discussion of the major components and systems that we use within IT and we're now...

00:31.000 --> 00:42.000
We're continuing our discussion of the major components and systems that we use within IT and we're now have arrived at distributed systems.

00:42.000 --> 00:43.000
So what are those, John?

00:43.000 --> 00:49.000
Yeah, distributed systems. I think the easiest way to think of what a distributed system is is a network.

00:49.000 --> 00:56.000
A distributed system is simply a bunch of devices, nodes that are connected to each other for whatever purpose.

00:56.000 --> 01:01.000
Either communications or sharing tasks or doing things that are important today.

01:01.000 --> 01:04.000
Think of a network as a distributed system.

01:04.000 --> 01:08.000
Yeah, the largest distributed system in the world is the Internet.

01:08.000 --> 01:11.000
Yeah, we use distributed systems all the time.

01:11.000 --> 01:14.000
So what's a grid computing then?

01:14.000 --> 01:20.000
Well, I think if you look at the slide here, it gives us a good indication of what grid computing is.

01:20.000 --> 01:32.000
Simply a whole bunch of devices that are connected to each other to work towards one common task so that they can all contribute and make the task much easier or even possible to achieve.

01:32.000 --> 01:34.000
In fact, I think you've got a pretty good example.

01:34.000 --> 01:39.000
Yeah, so there's this organization called SETI and they are looking for aliens, little green people.

01:39.000 --> 01:41.000
Why they always green? I don't know.

01:41.000 --> 01:47.000
Here's the problem with SETI. They're searching for aliens, but as you can imagine, they're not super well-funded.

01:47.000 --> 01:50.000
It's hard to get academic grants for looking for aliens.

01:50.000 --> 02:01.000
So SETI has managed over the years to get access to radio telescopes to listen to the night sky and to pick up the signals that ET might be sending, radio signals.

02:01.000 --> 02:06.000
And so SETI has managed to get time on radio telescopes and now they have all this data, but they have a big problem.

02:06.000 --> 02:14.000
They need to scan through this data to look for patterns and that takes a lot of computing power and they don't have any budgets.

02:14.000 --> 02:19.000
So what they figured out, and this is really cool, they did this like 20 years ago, it was called SETI at home.

02:19.000 --> 02:25.000
It was a screensaver you could install on your computer and what would happen is you would download your computer when the screensaver ran,

02:25.000 --> 02:32.000
would download a little slice of this radio data and then your computer would scan through that data looking for signals or aliens.

02:32.000 --> 02:37.000
And then when your computer was done, it would send back that little slice of data to the SETI organization and you'd get the new one.

02:37.000 --> 02:48.000
And they called the SETI at home and they made a bit of a, they kind of gamified it, they made a bit of a competition out of it where there was a leader board as to exactly how many people were computing so many chunks of data per day and so forth.

02:48.000 --> 02:52.000
And it ended up being at the time the largest grid computer in the world.

02:52.000 --> 02:57.000
There was millions of systems all working on this at once and so that created a massive grid computer.

02:57.000 --> 03:01.000
And that's what grid computing is, a whole bunch of systems working together trying to solve a single problem.

03:01.000 --> 03:27.000
Yep and you know obviously we have to relate this to security correct so if you look at the slide that you have in front of you, you know that's what the architecture looks like but from a security perspective you need to protect not only that server in the middle for example that drives everything but also all of the individual components that are part of that grid computing architecture because they may have very valuable information that belongs to organizations.

03:27.000 --> 03:34.000
So just like anything else you have to break the architecture down into components and to protect each one as we know.

03:34.000 --> 03:37.000
Next topic, data warehouses, what are those John?

03:37.000 --> 03:52.000
Well companies have been doing this because you know when you look at the history of databases companies have been building databases so that we can store valuable and meaningful information in these formats.

03:52.000 --> 03:58.000
But then you know looking at the databases and updating them is what drives business decisions.

03:58.000 --> 04:09.000
And so we found value because historically we had different databases that companies had built for different purposes and they may have their own little data store.

04:09.000 --> 04:17.000
And if you're trying to analyze the data in a centralized place, if you're trying to analyze data it's very hard to do that when it's all fragmented spread across all these systems.

04:17.000 --> 04:44.000
Yeah so companies figured out that there's value in taking all of this different information possibly in different formats and putting it all together because if you put information all together gives you the ability to analyze that data and you can find much more meaningful information related to what trends, relationships, correlations, patterns, all of that invisible data that is now visible because you put everything together.

04:44.000 --> 04:50.000
Yeah to make better business decisions is what it's all about. But of course now the no one wants to talk about data warehouses anymore.

04:50.000 --> 05:00.000
The new sexy thing is of course big data. So what's the difference between a data warehouse and big data because the whole idea behind big data is that you bring in data from all these different sources and you analyze the data.

05:00.000 --> 05:04.000
It sounds just like a data warehouse. So what's the big difference?

05:04.000 --> 05:10.000
The way I like to remember it and it's pretty common in the industry you've got the three V's volume velocity and variety.

05:10.000 --> 05:18.000
And let's start with volume. With a data warehouse you tend to be restricted to the computing capacity capacity storage capacity of a single even high power system.

05:18.000 --> 05:29.000
But in big data you can store data across thousands of systems. And it's worth maybe taking a step back for a moment and think about where did big data actually come from? Where did this concept originate?

05:29.000 --> 05:36.000
And the creators, the idea where big data first came from was essentially Google because they had a pretty big data problem.

05:36.000 --> 05:43.000
They were trying to index the entire internet and then be able to search that entire internet in milliseconds. They're still proud of this to this date right.

05:43.000 --> 05:48.000
They'll show at the bottom of search page how many results how many millions of results were returned in like three milliseconds.

05:48.000 --> 05:55.000
And so they needed to store a huge amount of data. So that's the volume of data in a big data warehouse.

05:55.000 --> 06:03.000
In big data you can store your data set across thousands of systems and the other big thing variety.

06:03.000 --> 06:11.000
With data warehouses you could typically only store relational or nice and clean table database where there's rows and columns.

06:11.000 --> 06:19.000
But in big data you can store files, unorganized text, pictures, videos, so all this different variety of data.

06:19.000 --> 06:23.000
And then volume is just how quickly you can ingest it, analyze it, and output it. That's kind of the difference.

06:23.000 --> 06:26.000
But otherwise both of these are all about doing what?

06:26.000 --> 06:36.000
Well the whole purpose is to gain business intelligence, metadata, valuable information that can drive better decisions.

06:36.000 --> 06:39.000
And we often refer to that as data mining or analytics.

06:39.000 --> 06:43.000
Now there's two kind of major risks we have to be aware of with both of these, right?

06:43.000 --> 06:45.000
Inference and aggregation.

06:45.000 --> 06:52.000
Yeah, although you know what's important for us to understand is that aggregation on its own is not a problem.

06:52.000 --> 07:05.000
And neither is inference, correct? Because that's why we're putting information together to have the ability for us to be able to infer more business decisions and valuable information.

07:05.000 --> 07:10.000
So I mean this is the reason why we have databases and big data and so on.

07:10.000 --> 07:18.000
Data mining is all about aggregation putting things together and then being able to infer more sensitive valuable information.

07:18.000 --> 07:25.000
So this is why we do it. The problem is unauthorized inference and aggregation.

07:25.000 --> 07:34.000
Because if you put all of this information together to allow us to analyze it, you know that may be easier for unauthorized people to analyze information that you don't want them to do.

07:34.000 --> 07:42.000
You don't want them to be able to infer or making or inferring things that maybe they're not supposed to, even for real employees.

07:42.000 --> 07:46.000
So I've got a good example of this and I can talk about it because this was a real world event.

07:46.000 --> 07:51.000
It was published in a number of papers. It was actually quite a while ago, over six or seven years ago, I think.

07:51.000 --> 07:53.000
Here's the story. It's kind of a fun one.

07:53.000 --> 07:58.000
So a man walked into a target store and this guy was just irate. He was furious.

07:58.000 --> 08:04.000
He just managed to see the store manager and when he got into the store manager's office, he just unleashed on this poor store manager.

08:04.000 --> 08:08.000
What is wrong with you? What sort of soulless, heartless, disgusting, corporate.

08:08.000 --> 08:15.000
He was furious and the store manager just at first couldn't understand why this guy was so angry about because he was just like,

08:15.000 --> 08:19.000
off out of his mind. But as he started to cool down, the story came out.

08:19.000 --> 08:27.000
And what this guy was so incredibly angry about is that target had been sending pregnancy-related coupons to his teenage daughter.

08:27.000 --> 08:34.000
Basically saying is like, what is wrong with you people? Are you trying to encourage teen pregnancy? Like, do you have no morals? What is wrong with you?

08:34.000 --> 08:40.000
So this is what he was so incredibly upset about. So he just unleashed on the store manager and then he left.

08:40.000 --> 08:44.000
But then he came back a few days later. He asked to see the store manager again.

08:44.000 --> 08:48.000
And this time, he was a little calmer. In fact, he was a little sheepish.

08:48.000 --> 08:52.000
And when he got into the store manager's office, he said, I'm here to apologize.

08:52.000 --> 08:56.000
The reason he had to apologize, turns out she was pregnant.

08:56.000 --> 09:02.000
So here's the interesting question. How did Target know that his teenage daughter was pregnant before he knew?

09:02.000 --> 09:07.000
And to be clear, Target did know that his teenage daughter was pregnant before the dad knew.

09:07.000 --> 09:14.000
How? Well, to me, it's obvious. It was the store manager that got her pregnant.

09:14.000 --> 09:20.000
I mean, all comes Razor, maybe, you know, maybe even though it's not the real reason. No. Although I can make sense.

09:20.000 --> 09:27.000
The real reason they knew is, inference and aggregation, Target collects a huge amount of data on their customers.

09:27.000 --> 09:33.000
They've got, you know, all their brick and mortar stores, all their online presence. They track whatever people are buying.

09:33.000 --> 09:40.000
They used to have, maybe they still do not an expert on Target, but they used to, they have drug stores in their stores.

09:40.000 --> 09:43.000
So they would know what sort of drugs you were buying. They had their red card.

09:43.000 --> 09:47.000
So they were able to track user purposes. They even had debit card or I think credit card services.

09:47.000 --> 09:51.000
They knew a lot of financial information. And then they do what all these big companies do.

09:51.000 --> 09:55.000
They combine that through sources like Lexus Nexus and with other things like Google and Facebook.

09:55.000 --> 10:04.000
And it is remarkable how much these big organizations know about an individual. They'll know your age, your gender, your race, where you live, your socio-economic situation.

10:04.000 --> 10:11.000
And they know exactly what you're buying. And they employ huge teams of data scientists to look for these little indicators.

10:11.000 --> 10:19.000
Like if you suddenly switch from scented to unscented hand cream and you start buying this versus that, then the probability that you're pregnant goes way up.

10:19.000 --> 10:22.000
And that's exactly what they were measuring. And that's how they knew.

10:22.000 --> 10:26.000
And so the thing I was like to think about here was, was what Target was doing illegal. And I don't want to be clear here.

10:26.000 --> 10:33.000
Like all the big companies do this. I'm not just picking on Target here. But was what Target was what they were doing, was it illegal?

10:33.000 --> 10:37.000
And the answer is absolutely not. It was creepy, but not illegal.

10:37.000 --> 10:44.000
And maybe just to finish this one off, there's one little funny piece here. And that is, so did Target change their ways? Did they suddenly stop doing this?

10:44.000 --> 10:49.000
No, they just got smarter. They still send out all sorts of targeted advertising, but they make it look less targeted.

10:49.000 --> 10:56.000
They'll throw in, instead of just being all pregnancy related items, they'll throw in a lawn tractor and a pool table or something else to make it look less targeted.

10:56.000 --> 11:02.000
So that's the problem of unauthorized inference and aggregation. It's not just Target that does it.

11:02.000 --> 11:10.000
I'm sure Walmart and other retailers and other industries do it as well. It's all available. It's easy to put all of that information together.

11:10.000 --> 11:17.000
Let me share one other example that I think really kind of highlights this. So think of a big bank, okay? Big banks often have multiple divisions.

11:17.000 --> 11:21.000
One division might be the stock traders. They're buying and selling stocks to try and make a profit.

11:21.000 --> 11:27.000
The other division is your M&A people. They are helping companies buy each other or buy each other, merge.

11:28.000 --> 11:35.000
Now, what would happen if the stock traders knew what the M&A people were up to? If they knew, for instance, that this company was about to buy that company?

11:35.000 --> 11:41.000
Would that be useful information to have to buy and sell stocks? It absolutely would be. But what do we call that, John?

11:41.000 --> 11:47.000
Business intelligence. We call that insider trading, and it is absolutely illegal.

11:47.000 --> 11:59.000
So that's a perfect example where even within one company, you've got to be very careful about what your employees are allowed to infer from what other employees may be doing because you can easily be guilty of insider trading.

11:59.000 --> 12:01.000
So how do we prevent this, John?

12:01.000 --> 12:14.000
Well, there is something that you need to remember. So for unauthorized inference and aggregation, the way that we can prevent to some degree, all of that, is through what we call poly instantiation.

12:14.000 --> 12:29.000
And if you take that word apart, poly means many, instantiation means instances. It really means allowing information to exist at different classification levels for the purpose of preventing unauthorized inference and aggregation.

12:29.000 --> 12:36.000
And we're actually going to look at this in more detail later on when we get into domain number eight, because it really applies there.

12:36.000 --> 12:44.000
We build poly instantiation techniques into our applications to prevent unauthorized risk of inference and aggregation.

